T~L~775~-655~0~#0000FF~~9pt~~~~comment~Note: There are probably no decoupling capacitors
required in this design. The RTKSimple Micro
board appears to have a decoupling cap connected
to VCC and ArduSimple says that "no external
components are required." However; adding some
additional decoupling caps is never a bad idea.
Use either through hole or SMD, not both.~1~start~gge228420~0~pinpart

T~L~760~-440~0~#0000FF~~9pt~~~~comment~Note: If you are not planning to connect a
radio you do not need these headers. You
can always solder them in later.
 
These headers are intended to allow
connection of an external radio to the F9P
serial 2 port.
 
This functionality is untested. Be wary of
the Pi's limited available current.~1~start~gge234182~0~pinpart

T~L~980~-145~0~#0000FF~~9pt~~~~comment~Note: You do not need 
a reset button if you
are able to power cycle
the SimpleRTK2B Micro~1~start~gge234473~0~pinpart

T~L~25~-260~0~#0000FF~~9pt~~~~comment~Note:
The 0.1" headers are not required and are only intended for ease of modification/troubleshooting.
 
- Without soldering headers; the pads make convenient points to probe during troubleshooting.
- Soldering male headers to the bottom of the PCB allows you to seat the PCB on a breadboard.
- Soldering male or female headers to the top of the PCB allows you to connect jumper wires.
- You could solder wires to the pads.~1~start~gge234635~0~pinpart
